cs.NE, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.SY, cs.RO 

This paper is about using surrogate models to improve the data-efficiency of neuroevolution algorithms. Specifically, it introduces a new algorithm that combines the Neuroevolution of Augmenting Topologies (NEAT) algorithm with a surrogate model built using a compatibility distance kernel. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Additionally, the paper uses kernel-based surrogate models, which are a popular technique in machine learning and optimization, suggesting that it could also be classified under cs.LG (Machine Learning) or cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also deals with control tasks, such as the cart-pole swing-up problem and the half-cheetah running task, which could place it under cs.SY (Systems and Control) or cs.RO (Robotics).
